{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \SA, top of your five-card suit against the heart game — take a look at dummy before committing further.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Welcome to the squeeze. You are in 4\H needing ten tricks, and after the obvious losers — a spade, the trump ace, the club king — the count comes up one short: nine winners, ten needed, and no finesse in sight that helps. Here is the new tool: when your own tricks run out, run your winners ANYWAY and watch the discards. A defender who has to guard two suits at once will, on the last winner, have to abandon one of them. Your job is only to notice which.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West takes the \SA and the defense collects its aces and the club king along the way — your count is now rectified: you have lost everything you can afford. Draw trumps, cash your top cards, and then lead dummy's LAST spade — the squeeze card. Watch East: he must keep his diamonds or dummy's ten scores, so at last the club QUEEN drops from his hand. Now your \CJ — a card that was a loser all evening — wins trick thirteen. Ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] That was a simple squeeze: two threats — dummy's diamond ten and your club jack — and one defender responsible for both. You did nothing clever except cash your winners in the right order and WATCH. Remember the feeling of that last spade hitting the table: the defender's problem is unsolvable, and his discard tells you the answer. The nine and the jack you were taught to finesse with — here they simply waited for the queen to leave.}
