{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D3, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against 6NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6NT needing twelve tricks, and the count says ELEVEN: five spades, three hearts in time, the two minor-suit aces and the club king. No finesse for the twelfth. So the squeeze — and its first commandment: RECTIFY THE COUNT. A squeeze only bites when you can win every remaining trick but one, so give the defense its trick NOW, early, while you still control everything. Then run the spades and watch.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the diamond ace and immediately give a diamond back — East's king takes it, and your count is rectified with eleven tricks and eleven cards to come. Now the engine: FIVE rounds of spades. West must keep the heart queen guarded and the club queen-ten guarded, and dummy's long cards stare at him the whole way. On the fifth spade his hearts crack; two tricks later the club TEN goes. Cash the hearts, then clubs: jack, king — his queen falls — and dummy's NINE of clubs takes trick thirteen. Twelve tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The full classic: count eleven, rectify at trick three, run the long suit, and one defender guarding two suits collapsed on schedule. Notice that the machine that first played this hand went ONE DOWN — it never gave up the diamond, so the squeeze never bit. The trick you concede early is the trick that comes home doubled at the end: that is rectifying the count, and it is the heart of every squeeze you will ever play.}
